<!-- ============ BUYING GUIDE ============ -->
<section class="guide-section" id="guide">
  <div class="guide-inner">
    <div style="text-align:center; max-width:680px; margin:0 auto 56px;">
      <div class="section-label">Buying Guide</div>
      <h2 class="section-title">How to Choose the Best Red Light Panel</h2>
      <p class="section-desc">Six things we look at before recommending any red light therapy panel for full body use.</p>
    </div>
    <div class="guide-grid">
      <div class="guide-card">
        <div class="guide-num">01 — COVERAGE</div>
        <h3>Match Panel Size to Your Body</h3>
        <p>For a true red light therapy full body panel, look for at least 36 inches of vertical coverage, or a stackable/linkable design. Smaller panels still work — you'll just need more sessions to cover the same area.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="guide-card">
        <div class="guide-num">02 — WAVELENGTH</div>
        <h3>Look for 660nm + 850nm</h3>
        <p>The best red light panels output both red (660nm) and near-infrared (850nm). Red light reaches the skin surface; near-infrared penetrates deeper. Single-wavelength panels are usually a compromise.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="guide-card">
        <div class="guide-num">03 — IRRADIANCE</div>
        <h3>Compare Output at Distance</h3>
        <p>Marketing wattage often differs from the irradiance (mW/cm²) you actually receive at use distance — usually 6 inches. Look for manufacturer-stated values measured at the distance you plan to use.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="guide-card">
        <div class="guide-num">04 — FLICKER &amp; EMF</div>
        <h3>Quality of the Driver Matters</h3>
        <p>Cheap red light full body panels can flicker noticeably, which is uncomfortable during long sessions. The best red light panels use DC drivers with reduced flicker and lower EMF at use distance.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="guide-card">
        <div class="guide-num">05 — WARRANTY</div>
        <h3>Don't Skip the Fine Print</h3>
        <p>Look for a multi-year warranty and a brand with responsive support. LEDs can degrade over time, so coverage on diode failure within the warranty window is genuinely valuable for a long-term purchase.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="guide-card">
        <div class="guide-num">06 — RETURNS</div>
        <h3>Check Current Return Policy</h3>
        <p>Before purchasing, verify the current return window and warranty terms on the product's Amazon listing — these can vary by seller and change over time. Buying from the brand or Amazon directly typically offers the most consistent terms.</p>
      </div>
    </div>
  </div>
</section>

